          "body": "Verses 5-9 form the psalm's lament proper, painting the enemies in escalating layers of treachery. First, distant adversaries speak malice and wish David dead (41:5). Then a pseudo-friend visits — not out of care but to gather intelligence — gathering wickedness in his heart and spreading it as soon as he leaves (41:6). Then a circle of whisperers conspires, devising harm and pronouncing a quasi-theological verdict: 'a wicked thing is poured out upon him' (41:8) — implying that his illness is divine punishment, that God has finished with him. But the deepest blow is reserved for verse 9: the *ish shelomi*, the 'man of my peace,' the intimate covenant companion who shared David's bread. The shared table in the ancient Near East was a bond of mutual loyalty and protection (cf. Genesis 31:54; 1 Samuel 20:34). To eat bread together and then lift the heel — an act of contempt, possibly alluding to striking with the foot — is treachery at its most personal. Jesus himself cited this verse (John 13:18) in reference to Judas Iscariot, making Psalm 41:9 a messianic text of first-order importance: the betrayal David suffered was the pattern the Son of David would fulfill perfectly and infinitely."
